247
00:09:41,127 --> 00:09:42,960
we've got everything
start to finish, right?

248
00:09:42,960 --> 00:09:45,293
We have to control every
aspect of those servers outside

249
00:09:45,293 --> 00:09:47,760
of building the server
itself, to some extent,

250
00:09:47,760 --> 00:09:49,468
or at least the
components in the server.

251
00:09:49,468 --> 00:09:52,762
You might still be
assembling the server rack.

252
00:09:52,762 --> 00:09:56,130
If you move, then, to hosting
a database on an EC2 instance,

253
00:09:56,130 --> 00:09:59,193
which we'll do, then you'll
see that OK, well, you still

254
00:09:59,193 --> 00:10:01,110
have to manage quite a
bit of stuff-- scaling,

255
00:10:01,110 --> 00:10:06,090
availability, backups, patches,
software installs, OS patches.

256
00:10:06,090 --> 00:10:08,800
But you don't really have
to handle the initial OS

257
00:10:08,800 --> 00:10:11,610
install, the general
maintenance of the servers,

258
00:10:11,610 --> 00:10:16,450
the power, the cooling
of those servers, again,

259
00:10:16,450 --> 00:10:18,640
cooling being a huge,
huge part of it.

260
00:10:18,640 --> 00:10:21,960
I think I told that story
about one of our data

261
00:10:21,960 --> 00:10:24,450
centers flooding at one
of my previous jobs.

262
00:10:24,450 --> 00:10:26,770
One of the AC units leaked
or something like that.

263
00:10:26,770 --> 00:10:30,510
And the water was slowly
creeping towards our servers,

264
00:10:30,510 --> 00:10:32,920
and that is obviously not ideal.

265
00:10:32,920 --> 00:10:34,957
So keeping that
in mind, that you

266
00:10:34,957 --> 00:10:37,290
don't have to worry about
that in those kind of outages,

267
00:10:37,290 --> 00:10:41,670
is a huge benefit, even if
you're just doing that approach.

268
00:10:41,670 --> 00:10:44,790
And then finally, on the
most extreme end outside

269
00:10:44,790 --> 00:10:48,030
of optimizing your individual
application, which again is just

270
00:10:48,030 --> 00:10:50,230
doing your coding
side of things,

271
00:10:50,230 --> 00:10:53,630
everything else is going to
be completely managed by AWS,

272
00:10:53,630 --> 00:10:54,130
right?

273
00:10:54,130 --> 00:10:55,588
They're going to
manage the scaling

274
00:10:55,588 --> 00:10:57,937
availability, backups software.

275
00:10:57,937 --> 00:10:59,520
And that's assuming
again, that you're

276
00:10:59,520 --> 00:11:02,110
using one of their managed
like Amazon RDS or Amazon

277
00:11:02,110 --> 00:11:04,360
Aurora, which we'll talk
about what those mean.

278
00:11:04,360 --> 00:11:06,460
But that is the kind
of extreme end of it,

279
00:11:06,460 --> 00:11:08,612
of you're not touching anything.

280
00:11:08,612 --> 00:11:10,320
They've got it all
taken care of for you.

281
00:11:12,970 --> 00:11:16,070
So then onto what RDS is.

282
00:11:16,070 --> 00:11:19,330
So it stands for Relational
Database Service.

283
00:11:19,330 --> 00:11:21,580
So you might even have
recognized that acronym before.

284
00:11:21,580 --> 00:11:23,163
It's a pretty general
purpose acronym.

285
00:11:23,163 --> 00:11:25,750
But specifically we're going
to be talking about Amazon RDS.

286
00:11:25,750 --> 00:11:29,140
And so the basic
building block of RDS

287
00:11:29,140 --> 00:11:31,327
is the database
instance itself, right?

288
00:11:31,327 --> 00:11:33,160
That is what the one
thing we need to define

289
00:11:33,160 --> 00:11:35,890
is, what is this database
instance, and really,

290
00:11:35,890 --> 00:11:37,160
what does it look like?

291
00:11:37,160 --> 00:11:41,020
So it's just a
database environment.

292
00:11:41,020 --> 00:11:43,490
It can contain multiple
user-created databases.

293
00:11:43,490 --> 00:11:45,910
It's just the
environment in which

294
00:11:45,910 --> 00:11:47,750
these databases are hosted.

295
00:11:47,750 --> 00:11:51,470
And you can choose amongst
these database engines.

296
00:11:51,470 --> 00:11:54,350
These are the ones that
are built into Amazon RDS.

297
00:11:54,350 --> 00:11:57,170
You can't really-- at
least as far as I'm aware,

298
00:11:57,170 --> 00:12:00,160
you can't bring in
any other flavors

299
00:12:00,160 --> 00:12:02,290
of a database
engine for yourself

300
00:12:02,290 --> 00:12:03,890
that you may have
been using already.

301
00:12:03,890 --> 00:12:05,090
You're kind of
constrained to using this,

302
00:12:05,090 --> 00:12:07,382
but that's also because,
again, it's a managed service.

303
00:12:07,382 --> 00:12:09,880
So they need to write all the
code on the back end for them

304
00:12:09,880 --> 00:12:13,870
to handle the scaling, the
backups, availability, patching,

305
00:12:13,870 --> 00:12:14,870
and all that good stuff.

306
00:12:14,870 --> 00:12:18,130
So you're constrained to
what you can use with--

307
00:12:18,130 --> 00:12:21,760
Amazon Aurora being an actual
first-party Amazon solution,

308
00:12:21,760 --> 00:12:23,780
and the other's coming
from other sources.

309
00:12:23,780 --> 00:12:28,240
But either way, that usually
covers most of the industry.

310
00:12:28,240 --> 00:12:32,770
I personally have only ever
worked with the top three there,

311
00:12:32,770 --> 00:12:34,528
but I know that you
all have probably

312
00:12:34,528 --> 00:12:36,820
been exposed to Oracle,
depending on what course you've

313
00:12:36,820 --> 00:12:38,720
taken to this, or Postgres.

314
00:12:38,720 --> 00:12:42,950
So again, for most
companies and organizations,

315
00:12:42,950 --> 00:12:43,805
this is sufficient.

316
00:12:43,805 --> 00:12:45,430
But be mindful that
you are constrained

317
00:12:45,430 --> 00:12:48,130
to these six database engines.

318
00:12:48,130 --> 00:12:51,590
But you can control your CPU,
memory, network performance.

319
00:12:51,590 --> 00:12:54,670
You can set max amounts on
memory and CPU consumption

320
00:12:54,670 --> 00:12:57,850
and what network performance
is actually absolutely needed

321
00:12:57,850 --> 00:12:59,000
for your task.

322
00:12:59,000 --> 00:13:02,450
So if it's not needing
top-end specs of everything,

323
00:13:02,450 --> 00:13:05,172
then save that money and get
the minimum solution, right?

324
00:13:05,172 --> 00:13:06,880
That'll depend on your
business use case,

325
00:13:06,880 --> 00:13:08,270
and that's something
for you to think about.

326
00:13:08,270 --> 00:13:09,840
But that's what
we're saying there.

327
00:13:12,610 --> 00:13:14,030
So the way it's--

328
00:13:14,030 --> 00:13:16,990
or better said, one
way it can be hosted

329
00:13:16,990 --> 00:13:19,190
is in a virtual
private cloud, right?

330
00:13:19,190 --> 00:13:22,540
Remember, VPC stands for
Virtual Private Cloud.

331
00:13:22,540 --> 00:13:26,020
And so that is just a
completely isolated environment

332
00:13:26,020 --> 00:13:29,420
of the AWS cloud for you or
your organization to work in.

333
00:13:29,420 --> 00:13:31,490
It's completely
logical isolation.

334
00:13:31,490 --> 00:13:35,440
Now, it can-- yeah, I'm pretty
sure your availability zone can

335
00:13:35,440 --> 00:13:38,320
stretch, or your VPC can stretch
across multiple availability

336
00:13:38,320 --> 00:13:39,170
zones.

337
00:13:39,170 --> 00:13:42,880
But it still is,
again, treating it

338
00:13:42,880 --> 00:13:46,340
as a logically independent
portion of the cloud.

339
00:13:46,340 --> 00:13:47,420
So it's for you only.

340
00:13:47,420 --> 00:13:49,490
You have to choose
who has access to it.

341
00:13:49,490 --> 00:13:51,990
So you can see here you have
to create this internet gateway

342
00:13:51,990 --> 00:13:54,220
to provide access
to those resources.

343
00:13:54,220 --> 00:13:58,610
You can create your
own IP address range--

344
00:13:58,610 --> 00:14:00,670
sorry, I'm talking
too fast today--

345
00:14:00,670 --> 00:14:04,480
create subnets, configure the
routing access control lists.

346
00:14:04,480 --> 00:14:06,970
Again, access control lists
will control who can access.

347
00:14:10,400 --> 00:14:11,090
Oh, yeah.

348
00:14:11,090 --> 00:14:12,465
And then I gave
this example here

349
00:14:12,465 --> 00:14:15,640
that the database
instance is often

350
00:14:15,640 --> 00:14:17,860
isolated in a private
subnet, meaning

351
00:14:17,860 --> 00:14:21,730
that really nobody is or
should be directly accessing

352
00:14:21,730 --> 00:14:25,780
it, the private subnet
that's sitting down here that

353
00:14:25,780 --> 00:14:28,880
houses our RDS instance.

354
00:14:28,880 --> 00:14:34,210
Instead, we will provide access
to specific users' applications

355
00:14:34,210 --> 00:14:36,430
to the resources
necessary in that.

356
00:14:36,430 --> 00:14:39,550
But again, common practice,
principles of least privilege,

357
00:14:39,550 --> 00:14:43,180
or minimum privilege,
whatever, just because we

358
00:14:43,180 --> 00:14:45,620
want to ensure that nobody's
unnecessarily writing,

359
00:14:45,620 --> 00:14:48,680
reading, or even worse, deleting
from this database, right?

360
00:14:48,680 --> 00:14:51,340
So these are all considerations
that we can have,

361
00:14:51,340 --> 00:14:53,355
and you can leverage
this in a VPC.

362
00:14:55,953 --> 00:14:56,870
Oh, yeah, there we go.

363
00:14:56,870 --> 00:14:58,245
So, yeah, you can
see that we can

364
00:14:58,245 --> 00:15:02,420
do a VPC in multiple
availability zones.

365
00:15:02,420 --> 00:15:05,330
A common reason
you'd want to do this

366
00:15:05,330 --> 00:15:07,980
is imagine you are an
international company,

367
00:15:07,980 --> 00:15:12,800
if you have locations in San
Francisco, Logan, and Hong Kong.

368
00:15:12,800 --> 00:15:17,990
And you want your employees,
who are data scientists or data

369
00:15:17,990 --> 00:15:20,910
analysts, whatever, whoever
needs to access this database,

370
00:15:20,910 --> 00:15:22,760
maybe even just an
application that's

371
00:15:22,760 --> 00:15:24,620
running at those
locations, you don't

372
00:15:24,620 --> 00:15:31,220
want them to have to really wait
on the data transfer speeds to--

373
00:15:31,220 --> 00:15:33,500
if they have a
query in Hong Kong

374
00:15:33,500 --> 00:15:35,420
and the data is
hosted in Logan, you

375
00:15:35,420 --> 00:15:37,760
don't want them to have
to wait the extra lag

376
00:15:37,760 --> 00:15:40,500
time of sending that query
all the way across the world

377
00:15:40,500 --> 00:15:43,080
and then back across once
they have a response.

378
00:15:43,080 --> 00:15:48,320
Instead, you can create this
second availability zone

379
00:15:48,320 --> 00:15:52,260
for your database, where
basically the transactions,

380
00:15:52,260 --> 00:15:55,800
the individual rows, those
get rep synchronously.

381
00:15:55,800 --> 00:15:58,490
So as they come in, they
get replicated to the copy.

382
00:15:58,490 --> 00:16:02,010
And so because of that, you'll
have this second version here,

383
00:16:02,010 --> 00:16:05,220
where if they make
a query, they're

384
00:16:05,220 --> 00:16:08,260
just going to hit this query in
their closest availability zone.

385
00:16:08,260 --> 00:16:10,050
It's up to date.

386
00:16:10,050 --> 00:16:12,150
Even though there's
a time for the data

387
00:16:12,150 --> 00:16:14,610
to transfer from wherever
its original location is

388
00:16:14,610 --> 00:16:17,293
over to here, that's going
to only have to happen once.

389
00:16:17,293 --> 00:16:18,960
It's not every single
query that happens

390
00:16:18,960 --> 00:16:20,500
has to go all the way across.

391
00:16:20,500 --> 00:16:22,250
So we're going to save
on transfer speeds.

392
00:16:22,250 --> 00:16:24,610
We're just going to save
costs, time, resources,

393
00:16:24,610 --> 00:16:26,670
all that good stuff.

394
00:16:26,670 --> 00:16:29,760
Another benefit of this is
that if the main database

395
00:16:29,760 --> 00:16:30,310
fails, right?

396
00:16:30,310 --> 00:16:33,160
Imagine this M here
represents our main database.

397
00:16:33,160 --> 00:16:35,940
If that main database
fails, then RDS

398
00:16:35,940 --> 00:16:38,080
will automatically bring
the standby instance

399
00:16:38,080 --> 00:16:40,540
online as the main instance.

400
00:16:40,540 --> 00:16:43,380
Even if you're just doing
a planned maintenance,

401
00:16:43,380 --> 00:16:44,740
planned system maintenance--

402
00:16:44,740 --> 00:16:46,620
I need to update the OS
or the security patch

403
00:16:46,620 --> 00:16:48,162
or something like
that-- well, great.

404
00:16:48,162 --> 00:16:50,550
I can take this instance down.

405
00:16:50,550 --> 00:16:52,510
I can just shut down
this main instance,

406
00:16:52,510 --> 00:16:56,190
make the private subnet the
main instance-- or sorry,

407
00:16:56,190 --> 00:16:58,170
the private subnet,
the second availability

408
00:16:58,170 --> 00:17:02,940
zone the main instance and
then do my updates here.

409
00:17:02,940 --> 00:17:06,220
Once this is done, switch it
back to being the main instance,

410
00:17:06,220 --> 00:17:07,650
and I can do my updates here.

411
00:17:07,650 --> 00:17:09,640
So I kind of have an
ongoing backup here.

412
00:17:09,640 --> 00:17:14,220
So the multi-availability zone
approach has a lot of benefits,

413
00:17:14,220 --> 00:17:18,602
and definitely recommend if it
is a tool or a solution that

414
00:17:18,602 --> 00:17:21,060
presents itself whenever you
find yourself in that position

415
00:17:21,060 --> 00:17:21,852
to make a decision.

416
00:17:24,510 --> 00:17:27,190
Similar to that is
creating a read replica--

417
00:17:27,190 --> 00:17:30,690
here I can kind of duck out of
the way, read replica instance.

418
00:17:30,690 --> 00:17:32,807
And it does exactly
what it sounds like.

419
00:17:32,807 --> 00:17:34,390
So it takes the--
or better statement,

420
00:17:34,390 --> 00:17:37,770
it allows the load on the source
database, the original database,

421
00:17:37,770 --> 00:17:40,230
to be reduced by
just routing queries

422
00:17:40,230 --> 00:17:44,140
to this other database that is
just for reading from, right?

423
00:17:44,140 --> 00:17:46,840
So think about the
use case here, right?

424
00:17:46,840 --> 00:17:48,202
You have data scientists.

425
00:17:48,202 --> 00:17:50,160
And we actually had a
similar situation to this

426
00:17:50,160 --> 00:17:51,040
at Carvana, right?

427
00:17:51,040 --> 00:17:53,370
We as data scientists
are constantly

428
00:17:53,370 --> 00:17:59,700
writing the worst big queries
to grab and join and reduce

429
00:17:59,700 --> 00:18:02,880
and filter out observations to
create a new data set or maybe

430
00:18:02,880 --> 00:18:05,580
a temp table or
something like that.

431
00:18:05,580 --> 00:18:07,658
But at the same time,
people are constantly

432
00:18:07,658 --> 00:18:09,450
interacting with the
website as well, which

433
00:18:09,450 --> 00:18:11,260
is generating new data points.

434
00:18:11,260 --> 00:18:13,800
And so if I first off,
kick off a query that

435
00:18:13,800 --> 00:18:16,500
maybe is running
live, it might never

436
00:18:16,500 --> 00:18:20,430
end if the statements are
coming in fast enough to keep it

437
00:18:20,430 --> 00:18:21,510
persisting.

438
00:18:21,510 --> 00:18:26,040
Or even worse, I can just kind
of bottleneck the server such

439
00:18:26,040 --> 00:18:28,470
that with my big query, I can
bottleneck the server such

440
00:18:28,470 --> 00:18:31,900
that it can't start
to collect new data.

441
00:18:31,900 --> 00:18:34,587
So I might miss out on
sales or anything else,

442
00:18:34,587 --> 00:18:36,420
or just create a bad
experience for the user

443
00:18:36,420 --> 00:18:38,000
because the user
hits the website

444
00:18:38,000 --> 00:18:39,750
and they can't pull
up any of the vehicles

445
00:18:39,750 --> 00:18:44,340
because the databases are
overloaded with my stupid query

446
00:18:44,340 --> 00:18:45,180
that I wrote.

447
00:18:45,180 --> 00:18:47,700
So this is the idea
behind a read replica,

448
00:18:47,700 --> 00:18:50,130
is that, well, I'll just
create a replica of the data

449
00:18:50,130 --> 00:18:53,680
at some sort of regular cadence.

450
00:18:53,680 --> 00:18:56,190
You can see here I can do it
in a different region, which

451
00:18:56,190 --> 00:18:58,630
will allow for more
disaster recovery

452
00:18:58,630 --> 00:19:02,970
if there's an issue with
that or a worry with that.

453
00:19:02,970 --> 00:19:06,510
And yeah, I never have to
worry about clogging up

454
00:19:06,510 --> 00:19:09,880
this main or primary
database instance.

455
00:19:09,880 --> 00:19:12,330
And so I just create this
read replica, read from that.

456
00:19:12,330 --> 00:19:14,280
Or any read queries
will read from there.

457
00:19:14,280 --> 00:19:18,370
And then everything can still be
updating in my primary instance.

458
00:19:18,370 --> 00:19:22,090
And then at some regular cadence
we just update the read replica.

459
00:19:22,090 --> 00:19:23,810
It could even be
synchronous, right?

460
00:19:27,770 --> 00:19:32,660
And so then question is, when
to use RDS versus potentially

461
00:19:32,660 --> 00:19:34,610
exploring other tools?

462
00:19:34,610 --> 00:19:37,790
I would say for
most of your actions

463
00:19:37,790 --> 00:19:41,370
as a student, or even
as early employee,

464
00:19:41,370 --> 00:19:43,460
you likely won't be
doing things that are

465
00:19:43,460 --> 00:19:45,630
exceeding the capacity of RDS.

466
00:19:45,630 --> 00:19:47,280
But that's not
always true, right?

467
00:19:47,280 --> 00:19:48,800
So just keep it in mind.

468
00:19:48,800 --> 00:19:51,480
Complex transactions,
very complex queries,

469
00:19:51,480 --> 00:19:54,230
it's maybe not the
most efficient.

470
00:19:54,230 --> 00:19:56,810
Again, analytics teams can
really, a lot of times,

471
00:19:56,810 --> 00:20:00,170
push the boundary of what's
an acceptable query for RDS

472
00:20:00,170 --> 00:20:01,290
or one of these tools.

473
00:20:01,290 --> 00:20:02,840
And that's where they may
want to explore something

474
00:20:02,840 --> 00:20:05,090
like Redshift, which we'll
talk about in a little bit.

475
00:20:05,090 --> 00:20:08,460
A medium to high
query or write rate,

476
00:20:08,460 --> 00:20:11,600
which they deem as anything
up to 30,000 input/output

477
00:20:11,600 --> 00:20:16,302
operations per second, 15,000
reads plus 15,000 writes,

478
00:20:16,302 --> 00:20:19,282
anything that's at that scale
or kind of exceeding that scale,

479
00:20:19,282 --> 00:20:21,240
you might want to look
at some other solutions.

480
00:20:21,240 --> 00:20:23,823
That's a lot read and writes per
second, I'll say that, right?

481
00:20:23,823 --> 00:20:27,270
15,000 read and write
operations per second,

482
00:20:27,270 --> 00:20:29,560
I think it's going to be
OK for most of your usage,

483
00:20:29,560 --> 00:20:31,500
but that's not to say
it's impossible, right?

484
00:20:31,500 --> 00:20:33,720
There, again, very clearly,
many businesses that

485
00:20:33,720 --> 00:20:34,860
are doing this, right?

486
00:20:34,860 --> 00:20:36,430
If I'm working with
financial data,

487
00:20:36,430 --> 00:20:40,140
I might be getting just
countless data points

488
00:20:40,140 --> 00:20:43,303
per second, and I might be
doing a bunch of processing

489
00:20:43,303 --> 00:20:44,970
and querying and
subsetting and creating

490
00:20:44,970 --> 00:20:46,480
of new data sets on the fly.

491
00:20:46,480 --> 00:20:48,420
